SQL is a standard language for accessing and manipulating databases.

What is SQL?
SQL stands for structured query language, it became the stander of the American national standards institute (ANSI) IN 1986 and the international organization from standardization (ISO) in 1987.

What can SQL do?
Execute queries against a database, retrieve data from a database, insert records in a database, update records, delete records, create new databases, create new tables, create stored procedures in a database , create views in a databases, set permissions on tables, procedures and views.

RDBMS- standard for relational database management system.
RDBMS is the basis for SQL, and all modern database systems.
The data in RDBMS is stored in database objects call tables. A table is collection of related dat entries and it consists for columns and rows.

Every table is broken up in smaller entities called fields. A field is a column in a table that is designed to maintain specific information about every record in the table.

Row - a record, also called a row, is each individual entry that exists in a table.
Column - is a vertical entity in a table that contains all information associated with a specific in a table.